<DOC><DOCNO> AP890530-0088 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-30-89 1124EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-NATO     05-30 0231</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Soviet-NATO,0237</SECOND><HEAD>Shevardnaze Says Bush Proposal Step in Right Direction</HEAD><HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze todaycalled President Bush's proposals for troop cuts in Europe aserious step in the right direction.   In his address to the first day of an East-West conference onhuman rights, Shevardnadze said the Soviet delegation at Viennatalks on conventional disarmament would be ready to discuss theideas in detail.   Bush has proposed cutting American and Soviet troops to 275,000on each side and negotiating new ceilings for tanks, aircraft andother conventional weapons on the European continent.   ``We consider the declaration made by President Bush in Brusselsas a serious and important step in the right direction,''Shevardnadze said.   Shevardnadze said the Soviet Union had been calling on theUnited States to reduce troops and arms in Europe ``in the contextof a reduction of a general level of confrontation on thecontinent.''   In briefer comments to reporters on his arrival, Shevardnazesaid Bush's proposals would be studied carefully.   But he added, ``It will take time to examine the Americanproposals in detail and determine the position of the USSR.''   Shevardnadze told reporters that Bush's proposal to acceleratethe pace of Vienna negotiations on conventional disarmament was``attractive,'' but said, ``Only experience will tell how much timeit will take to arrive at mutually acceptable solutions.''</TEXT></DOC>